1.	Explain the role of Amazon Web Services IAM in cloud security. Mention its key features.
AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) is a security service provided by Amazon Web Services (AWS) that helps control access to AWS resources. It allows administrators to securely manage who can access cloud services and what actions they can perform.
Key Roles of IAM in Cloud Security
•	Provides authentication by verifying the identity of users and services. 
•	Enables authorization by defining permissions for accessing AWS resources. 
•	Protects cloud resources from unauthorized access. 
•	Supports the principle of least privilege, ensuring users receive only the permissions they need. 
•	Enhances overall security through centralized access management. 
Key Features of AWS IAM
•	Users and Groups – Create individual users and organize them into groups for easier permission management. 
•	Roles – Assign temporary permissions to users, applications, or AWS services. 
•	Policies – Define permissions using JSON-based policy documents. 
•	Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) – Adds an extra layer of security during login. 
•	Fine-Grained Access Control – Control access to specific AWS resources and actions. 
•	Federated Access – Allows users from external identity providers to access AWS resources.
